{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_rigoletto_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608786/1958061001/0882.xml":{"full_text":"r t*>\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nniMi\u00bbr, svn ia, iim\nA-6\n\u25a0BP .g^\n\u2022]j\nTES77NG A DO-IT-YOURSELF SUB\nKenneth Soderbeck (left) and Bill Somervill launch their homemade\nsubmarine at Center Lake, near Jackson, Mich. The 400-pound under\nwater craft was made from the wing tanks of a jet plane. It is powered\nby a war surplus motor converted to run from special waterless batteries\n\\n a pressurized motor compartment. The two occupants wear aqua\nlungs while submerged.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\n\nReckoning Day Near\nForTrade Bill Lobbyists\nFor lobbyists perched in the House galleries, this is a week\nof reckoning. Reciprocal trade comes up for a crucial vote\ntomorrow.\nLike fight trainers when the bell clangs, the lobbyists have\nnearly finished their job and now must sit and watch the\nbout run its course. They remain alert, however, to give\npep talks and whisper advice\nbetween rounds of debate.\nWhoever wins in the House\nmust meet a challenge in the\nSenate. The loser, of course,\nwill try to stage a Senate\ncomeback.\nWatching and listening from\nthe galleries are O. R. Strack\nbein and Mrs. George Bell\nleading strategists for the pro\ntectionists and liberal trade\nlobbies, respectively.\nFancy Labels\nTrue to custom, their groups\nwear fancy labels. Mr. Strack\nbein is chairman of the Nation-\nWide Committee of Industry,\nAgriculture and-Labor on Im\nport-Export Policy. Mrs. Bell\nis Washington director of the\nCommittee for a National Trade\nPolicy.\nMr. Strackbein apparently is\nthe more active in last-minute\noperations, perhaps because his\nside is considered the under\ndog in the House, He reported\ncontacting about eight Repre\nsentatives yesterday, calling\nsome of them off the floor to\nchat in the cloakroom and\nvisiting others at their offices.\n\u201cContacts will continue till\nthe final vote,\" he said in an\ninterview, because \u201cthe issue\nis very closely matched.\"\nUncommitted members\u2014per\nhaps 50 of them\u2014hold the bal\nance, Mr. Strackbein said. He\nworks closest with these \u201cfence\nsitters,\" who are looking for\narguments to justify a vote one\nway or the other. j|\nAn Answer for the Problem J\nFollowing what he calls\n\u201cstandard procedure,\u201d Mr.\nStrackbein explains the issues\nfrom his point of view, answers\ncontentions by the opposition\nand tries to find out what\nmakes a Representative hesi\ntate. When he discovers the\narea of doubt, he selects and\nuses the appropriate argument\nfrom the file in hfs brown hom\nburg hat.\nMr. Strackbein meet 3 few if\nany rebuffs to his approaches.\n\u201cThere is a very great disposi\ntion to listen.\" he remarked.\nWhile concentrating on un\ncommited Representatives, he\nalso leaves the gallery to con\nfer with those solidly in his\ncamp. He supplies facts, figures\ntactical advice and other am\nmunition to participants in de\nbate. And any lobbyist obli\ngates himself to help passive\nallies answer criticism from\nconstituents.\nFavors Country Support\nMrs. Bell said her group en\ngages in little \u201cstraight lob\nbying,\u201d although she, like Mr.\n\"..r i,r^iyc^s^g=||j^cs===;\n-^LMERICAN\nM9F University\nlm* __\nML Ws summer'\u201d\niilaBHSiP SESSION\ngKra|Vm| June 23-Augu* 29\nWB&zJ (Collett o) Low, ]unt 16\u2014August 22)\nPFPIQTRATIfIN rri-iy .JUNE 20, i2:3Ote7P.M.\nntmoiiuuiun WiJy JUNE 2 i, *.jo am. 1.1230 p.m.\n(College of Low Thors, mod Fri., June 12 and 12, 12.30-6.10 F.MJ\nDOWNTOWN CENTER \u2014l*ol P Street, N.W.\nUPTOWN CAMPUS \u2014Matt. A Nebraska Avei., N.W.\nCOLLEGE OF LAW \u20142OOO g street, n.w.\nFor complete detsils end course descriptions, phone\nIT Oodley 6-6RO), or write or visit the Director of\nAdmissions, Messmcbusetts end Sehrmskm Ave\u201e N.W.\nStrackbein, Is a registered lob\nbyist.\nInstead of taking the initia\ntive in contacting Congress\nmen, she continued, her strate\ngy is to stand ready with in\nformation when asked. \u201cI don\u2019t\nthink buttonholing is a very\neffective way of persuading\nmembers of Congress,\" she said\nin an interview.\nOn her way back to the of\nfice from Capitol Hill yester\nday, Mrs. Bell reported, about\nfive individuals asked her to\nsend them data.\n\u201cIt's not so important wheth\ner we go to see members of\nCongress,\u201d she said, as it is to\n\u201cstimulate support around the\ncountry.\u201d\nMrs. Bell was unable to esti\nmate how many letters and\nother contacts with Congress\nher committee and others have\ninspired. Anyway, she re\nmarked, \u201cit's better for Con\ngressmen to feel their constit\nuents are self-started and not\nnudged.\u201d\nThe committee puts out a\nlarge volume of slick litera\nture, including a \"do-it-your\nself\u201d brochure with suggestions\nto industry members on how\nto mobilize popular sentiment\nfor liberal trade.\nMrs. Bell referred disdain\nfully to opposition efforts to\n\u201cswamp\" Congress with mail)\ninspired, she said, partly j\nI through questionable pressure\ntactics. Mr. Strackbein, how-1\never, discounted the impact of\n'mass communications.\"\nt 100% 1\nj Air Conditioned 1\n2000 modem rooms\nVery sensible rates include\nTelevision ft Radio\n\u25a0Tt*#*** HOTEL\nTAFT\n.KNEW YORK\nON TIMES SQUARE AT RADIO CITY\nAltiH lewis. Oenersl Manlier\nAtom Blasts\nMay Be Used\nFor Harbor\nBf the Associated Presa\nIf studies show it is safe and\npracticable, the United States\nmay use atomic blasts to ex\n<*vate a harbor along Alaska\u2019s\ncoast north of the Arctic Circle.\nThe Atomic Energy Commis\njsion announced yesterday sur\nvey parties will study the site\nbetween Cape Seppings and\nCape Thompson this summer\nto determine whether the proj\nect is feasible.\nIf the findings are favorable,\nthe harbor could be excavated\nin 1960, the AEC statement\nsaid. It said lack of harbors\nalong Alaska\u2019s northwestern\ncoast has hampered develop\nment of mineral deposits and\nfishing.\nIn addition to providing data\non costs and various other\ntechnical aspects, the survey\nteams will determine whether\nthe project would endanger any\nlives, including fish and wild\nlife, within and outside the im\nmediate area.\nThe commission described\nthe harbor venture as part of\nits Project Plowshare to find\nnew peaceful uses for nuclear\nblasts.\nThe AEC said both Canada\nand Russia have been informed\nof the plan and that other na-\nMOTORISTS-j\nGet authorized factory service\non generators carburetors reg\nulators. fuel pumps starters\nwindshield wipers, distribu\ntors and small electric motors\nAlso electric window service\nBuell's Auto Electric Service\n811 lOtfc St NW ME 8-5777\nmet H and Eye Streets>\n4\nPhene ft-.sfOO, Yin it Coupon, or feme In for This?\npH\n|MT Rl MRAMCKin\n*Ht,T m VAUtT AT THE TOP AT TWf BOTTOM AT THE IgIT AW RtCHT\nPROCESS ROUSE 4-WAV GUARD/ AY\nMOTH-D-STROY STORAGE RAGS\nj\n57\" Double Jumbo Bag, 4.98 57\" 8-Dress Bag, 2.89\n57\" Jumbo Bag, 2.98 42\" Jumbo Suit Bag, 2.89\n\nMoth-killing vapor at top, sides! Cleor vinyl front; quilted top, matching tone\nsides! Sturdy metal frame, non-tilt hooks! Pink, aqua or green!\nj THE HECHT CO. (Dept. 7), Washington 4, D. C.\nPlease tend me the following Princess House 4-Woy Moth-D-Stroy Storage Bags; j\nj Quantity Size Color 2nd Color j Price\ni _j i i i\nI _ I i i i Jl\nI Print Nome J\nI I Address Apt. No. j\nJ City Zone County State i\nCl Charge Check or MO. CCO D. (25c handling charge)\nd Mdse Certificate (payable on locol delivery)\nj Add Saltt Tei II you lire In Weehintton or Maryland. Add tSc lor delivery and handling I\nJrlmreM beyond our tree delivery dree tor one tlem and Me lor each odd monel one. S-i-IO j\nTHE HECHT CO. j\nv NOTIONS, street Floor, Wetfii*\u00a7ton. Silter Spring A FARKtneton J\n_ Jf.\n,v. s\nFall Business Outlook\nBright, Weeks Says\nSecretary of Commerce\nWeeks today reported that\ni recent business statistics \u201chave\nlooked better than at any time\nsince the decline started last\nyear.\"\n\u201cTlie field day of the hand\nringing pessimist is about over,\u201d I\nMr. Weeks said in a speech pre\npared for the 43rd National\nConference on Weights and\nMeasures at the Sheraton-Park\nHotel.\n\u201cIf public confidence con-1\ntinues to glow, if business con\ntinues to spur the upturn, if\ngovernment continues to keep\naway from gumming tne works j\nby unsound legislation, the;\neconomy should continue to\nimprove.\u201d\n\u2022Mr. Weeks acknowledged that\nthe economy \u201cstill has some\nmonths to go before it recovers\ncomplete health.\u201d but aded \u201cthe\noutlook is bright for better\n[times later this year.\"\nThe Secretary noted that\nbusiness inventories were re\nduced by SBOO million in April.;\nThis suggests that many com- 1\npanies must soon go back to the\nmarket for new stocks, Mr.\nWeeks said.\nHe cited these other statis\ntics:\nSteel mill operations have\nadvanced from a low of 47 per\ncent of theoretical capacity in\nApril to 61 per cent last week.\nConstruction activity rose 10\nper cent in May over April, j\nEmployment In May climbed\nADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT\nMature Men and Women\nCan Make New Friends\nWhen most all your friends are\nmarried it is not too easy to keep\nup social contact. Nor are they 1\nable to introduce you to new\nfriends very often.\nThat is why Helen Leeds fills\nsuch a big need for so many re- j\nputable men and women.\nAfter planning the introduction 1\ncarefully on the basis of all im- 1\nport ant factors, we arrange the\ndate In very much the way a\nmutual friend might plan a\n\u201cblind date.\u201d\nUse Quality Paint\u2014lt Cost so little More\nWIMSIOW'\nHouse J* M I I l l\nSAMUEL CABOT'S\u2014WINSLOW'S\nBENJAMIN MOORE'S\nN* GOLD BOND VELVET\n-5418 Queens Chapel Rd. Hyatts, W\u00bb. 17772\n7514 Wise Ave Bethesda. Md. 01.4 4160\n5307 Balto Ave. Hyatts., Md. WA. 71180\n1239 Wisconsin Ave NW. Ft. 3 7667 /\"\u201crTCT\nFREE RAW INS A1 All STORES Supplies at All Stores\n1.200.000 while Joblessness\ndropped by 200,000.\nMr Weeks found reason for\noptimism in his department\u2019s\nannouncement Sunday that in- j\ndustry\u2019s planned outlays for,\nnew plants and equipment this\nyear will be s3l billion, a figure\n17 per cent below the record!\n$37 billion outlay of 1957.\nBut Mr. Weeks said the 1958\ntotal still will be the third high\nlest on record, exceeded only\njby 1956 and 1957.\nMd. U. Employe\nWaives Hearing\nA former University of Mary\nland employe yesterday waived a\npreliminary hearing on charges\nstemming from a fund shortage\nat the school.\nThe accused. Elliott M. El\nliott, 46, of 711 Gilbert street.\n|Takoma Park, was ordered held\nfor grand jury action after he\nwaived preliminary hearing in\nHyattsville Police Court on two\ncharges of grand larceny and!\nthree of forgery. The amount\ninvolved in the charges against\nElliott is $1,549.\nElliott was charged May 27\nby Detective Lt. Earl J. Huber\nafter he, university officials.'\nand the State auditor's office\ndisclosed a shortage of about\ni SIB,OOO in an account in the\n'College of Agriculture.\nIf you are an unmarried adult\n(single, widowed or divorced\ndon\u2019t just wait to meet someone\noy chance. See Helen Leeds. This!\niis the modem way to meet\npeople.\nI To get the full details, call I\nMEtropolitan 8-6818, Noon to 7\nP.M. daily, for a free, private'\ninterview.\nOr write to HELEN LEEDS'\nINTRODUCTION SERVICE, 712'\nWarner Bldg., 13th and E Sts..\nWashington 4, D. C., for litera-!\nture.\n\"Second Floor, Please\"\nI W*\nnow\nji jt 1 It Hit Tint I* Buy\n|jj \u2014gJr M Important Savings to You\n20% to 35%\nOn Hensons Nationally f amsNi Silverware the pat\nterns you admire most, and the manufacturers you know, and depend\nupon.\nOn Bensons Large Selection of Qualify Matches\nfamous names, and a wide variety of styles for men and women.\nOn Bensons Fine Jewelry an array of high-fashion\njewelry and the more conservative and age